mer|CB}}\n\n| special_teams =\n{{NFLplayer|&nbsp;7|Morten Andersen|K}}\n{{NFLplayer|10|Brian Hansen|d=American football|P}}\n\n| reserve_lists =\n\n| practice_squad =\n}}\n\n==Regular season==\n\n===Schedule===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-style=\"background:black;color:#BB8C3C;\"\n! Week\n! Date\n! Opponent\n! Result\n! Attendance\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 1\n| September 13, 1987\n| [[1987 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]]\n| W 28\u201321\n| <center>59,900</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ffdddd;\"\n| 2\n| September 20, 1987\n| at [[1987 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]]\n| L 27\u201321\n| <center>57,485</center>\n|-style=\"background:\"\n| \u2013\n| September 27, 1987\n| [[1987 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]]\n| canceled\n| \n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 3\n| October 4, 1987\n| [[1987 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]]\n| W 37\u201310\n| <center>29,745</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ffdddd;\"\n| 4\n| October 11, 1987\n| at [[1987 St. Louis Cardinals (NFL) season|St. Louis Cardinals]]\n| L 24\u201319\n| <center>11,795</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 5\n| October 18, 1987\n| at [[1987 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]]\n| W 19\u201317\n| <center>46,813</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ffdddd;\"\n| 6\n| October 25, 1987\n| [[1987 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]]\n| L 24\u201322\n| <center>60,497</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 7\n| November 1, 1987\n| at [[1987 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]]\n| W 38\u20130\n| <center>42,196</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 8\n| November 8, 1987\n| at [[1987 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]]\n| W 31\u201314\n| <center>43,379</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 9\n| November 15, 1987\n| at [[1987 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]]\n| W 26\u201324\n| <center>60,436</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 10\n| November 22, 1987\n| [[1987 New York Giants season|New York Giants]]\n| W 23\u201314\n| <center>67,639</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 11\n| November 29, 1987\n| at [[1987 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]]\n| W 20\u201316\n| <center>47,896</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 12\n| December 6, 1987\n| [[1987 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]]\n| W 44\u201334\n| <center>66,471</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 13\n| December 13, 1987\n| [[1987 Houston Oilers season|Houston Oilers]]\n| W 24\u201310\n| <center>68,257</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 14\n| December 20, 1987\n| at [[1987 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]]\n| W 41\u201324\n| <center>43,424</center>\n|-style=\"background: #ddffdd;\"\n| 15\n| December 27, 1987\n| [[1987 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]]\n| W 33\u201324\n| <center>68,364</center>\n|}\n\n===Standings===\n{{1987 NFC West standings}}\n\n==Playoffs==\n\n===NFC Wild Card Game===\n{{Americanfootballbox | title=Minnesota Vikings 44, New Orleans Saints 10\n|Road='''Vikings'''\n|R1=10\n|R2=21\n|R3=3\n|R4=10\n|RT=44\n|Home=Saints\n|H1=7\n|H2=3\n|H3=0\n|H4=0\n|HT=10\n|stadium= [[Louisiana Superdome]], [[New Orleans]]\n|time= 12:30 p.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]/11:30 a.m. [[Central Time Zone|CST]]\n|TV=[[NFL on CBS|CBS]]\n|TVAnnouncers= [[Pat Summerall]] and [[John Madden (football)|John Madden]]\n|attendance= 68,127\n}}\nIn the Saints' first playoff game in history, the Vikings dominated the game by recording two sacks, forcing four turnovers, and allowing only 149 yards. [[Anthony Carter (American football)|Anthony Carter]] returned a punt for a touchdown, and future Saints quarterback [[Wade Wilson (American football)|Wade Wilson]] threw a Hail Mary pass for a touchdown to [[Hassan Jones]] on the last play of the first half.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nor/1987.htm 1987 New Orleans Saints] at [[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]\n\n{{New Orleans Saints}}\n{{New Orleans Saints seasons}}\n{{1987 NFL season by team}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1987 New Orleans Saints season}}\n[[Category:1987 National Football League season by team|New Orleans]]\n[[Category:New Orleans Saints seasons]]\n[[Category:1987 in sports in Louisiana|New]]\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1987_New_Orleans_Saints_season"}
{"title_page": "St John's College, Hastings", "text_new": "{{For|other schools of the same name|Saint John's College (disambiguation){{!}}Saint John's College}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2019}}\n \n{{Infobox school\n|name         = St John's College\n|image        = \n|motto        = {{ubl|{{lang-la|[[List of Latin phrases (M-O)|Opere et Veritate]]}}|(\"In Word and in Deed\")}}\n|established  = 1941; {{years ago|1941}} years ago\n|type         = [[Secondary education in New Zealand|State Integrated]], [[Single-sex school|Single-sex]], [[Day school|Day]], Secondary (Year 9\u201313)\n|denomination = [[Catholic Church in New Zealand|Catholic]] \n|principal    = Paul Melloy\n|fees         = \n|city         = [[Hastings, New Zealand|Hastings]]\n|state        = [[Hawkes Bay]]\n|country      = [[New Zealand]] {{flagicon|New Zealand}}\n|coordinates  = {{coord|39|38|22|S|176|51|22|E|display=inline,title}}\n|roll = {{NZ school roll data|226|y||y}} <small>({{NZ school roll data|||y}})</small>\n|num_employ   = ~ 35 (full time)\n|decile =  4K<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.minedu.govt.nz/~/media/MinEdu/Files/EducationSectors/PrimarySecondary/SchoolOpsResourcing/OperationalFundingDeciles/DecileChanges_20142015.xls |title= Decile Change 2014 to 2015 for State & State Integrated Schools |publisher= Ministry of Education |accessdate= 12 February 2015}}</ref>\n|MOE =  226\n|revenue      = \n|colours      = Maroon, blue and white\n|homepage     = [http://www.stjohns.school.nz/ www.stjohns.school.nz]\n}}\n\n'''St John's College''' is a [[Secondary education in New Zealand|State Integrated]], [[Catholic Church in New Zealand|Catholic]], [[Day School]] for boys, located in [[Hastings, New Zealand|Hastings]], a provincial city in [[Hawkes Bay]], New Zealand.\n\nFounded in 1941 by the [[Society of Mary (Marists)|Marist Fathers]], St John's College has a non-selective enrolment policy (although gives preference to students from Catholic families) and currently caters for approximately 450 students from Year 9 (3rd Form) to Year 13 (7th Form).\n\nSt John's College has a diverse, multicultural roll. In 2006 its ethnic composition was P\u0101keh\u0101 73%, M\u0101ori 23%, and Pacific 4%\n.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ero.govt.nz/ERO/reppub.nsf/Institution/0C81B79B808D45E2CC2571220004ABBD/$File/226.htm?OpenElement#_Toc128809659|title=Education Review Report|work=Education Review Office|date=February 2006|accessdate=18 July 2008}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> The college excels in sporting and cultural activities. Academically, the school offers for senior years the [[National Certificate of Educational Achievement]] assessment system (NCEA).\n\nSt John's College is the oldest private/state integrated secondary for boys in New Zealand outside the traditional main centres of Auckland, Wellington, Christchurch, and Dunedin ([[Te Aute College]], also in Hawke's Bay was previously the title holder but became coed during the 1990s).\n\n== History ==\nSt John's College was established in 1941, on Frederick St, Hastings (the current site of St Mary's Primary School).  It was founded by the [[Society of Mary (Marists)|Marist Fathers]] in response to the lack of Catholic education for young men in Hawkes Bay. It was also to be a brother school to the already established all girls [[Sacred Heart College, Napier]], some 20&nbsp;km north.\n\nEnrolment proved so popular that the school needed to expand, so in 1956, with an allotment of donated land, St John's College moved to its present site on Jervois St, Mayfair. Old boys recall that on the day of the move, they carried the school furniture, back and forth to the new premises over 3&nbsp;km away, and still had to attend afternoon class. The roll grew more slowly after that. Part of the problem was the transportation of students from around the Hawkes Bay region as many students from Napier found it difficult to reach school before school bus lines were established. There were even calls to make both Sacred Heart and St Johns co-ed, to prevent Napier boys travelling to Hastings and Hastings girls travelling to Napier. Today this issue is non-existent, although around 40% of St John's College students come from the Napier area.\n\nIn 1975, St John's College was \"integrated\" into the state system under the ''Private Schools Conditional Integration Act 1975''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.govt.nz/libraries/contents/om_isapi.dll?clientID=3690096234&hitsperheading=on&infobase=pal_statutes.nfo&record=%7b3AAAD062%7d&softpage=DOC|title=Education Review Report|work=Education Review Office|date=February 2006|access-date=18 July 2008|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716023004/http://www.legislation.govt.nz/libraries/contents/om_isapi.dll?clientID=3690096234&hitsperheading=on&infobase=pal_statutes.nfo&record=%7b3AAAD062%7d&softpage=DOC|archive-date=16 July 2011|df=}}</ref> \"on a basis which will preserve and safeguard the special character of the education provided by them\".\n\nOver time St John's quietly expanded with the addition of new buildings and land. The 1990s saw drastic changes with the completion of 'The Centre' (the school gymnasium), the music suite and geography room, and the purchase of the old Firth industrial land to expand the playing fields. This gave St John's an additional rugby field, a new area for cricket nets, and another drive way towards Karamu road with additional car spaces. Since 2000 several remodels have been undertaken and includes the construction of the new technology wing.\n\nSt John's College celebrated its 50th Jubilee in 1991 which was easily the colleges biggest event ever. An abundance of old boys returned for the weekend and included several speakers and functions as well as a variety of activities and inter house competitions for the students.\n\nIn May 2014, the school suspended student Lucan Battison over the length of his hair.<ref>[http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/tweets-over-suspended-student-lands-schoolgirl-in-hotwater-6005703 Tweets over suspended student lands schoolgirl in hotwater]</ref> The family took the school to the High Court,<ref>[http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/back-school-boy-while-judge-ponders-long-hair-6009989 Back to school for boy while judge ponders long hair]</ref> where they won against the school.<ref>[http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/education/10207087/Lucan-Battison-wins-long-hair-court-battle Lucan Battison wins long-hair court battle]</ref>\n\n== Campus ==\nSt John's College is situated on Jervois St, Mayfair, in Hastings' northern suburbs. The site layout has all academic buildings close to the main road and are named after former rectors of the school, for example 'The Dowling Block' which contains the Library and Humanities subjects. Behind the buildings are the school playing fields, which separate the swimming pool and the tennis courts from the academic areas.\n\n===Facilities===\nCurrent facilities of St John's include:\n*'The Centre', which is a gymnasium used for sports, games and [[physical education]] (PE) classes. Also used as the venue for weekly Wednesday assemblies and other official school occasions such as college masses and the Year 12 Leavers' Mass.\n*The Kenneth Guthrie Pool, located at the rear of the school property, next to the tennis courts.\n*Playing Fields, which consists of a variety of interconnected fields containing two rugby fields, a cricket pitch and soccer field, field hockey students practice at Park Island Sports Ground in Napier.\n\n==St John's tradition==\n\n=== Crest ===\n\nThe school [[Coat of arms|crest]] incorporates four symbols. It incorporates the major elements of Archbishop Redwood's Crest the star and the AM as well as the \"Redwood Cross\" i.e. the cross on top of a pile of rocks. The five 5 pointed stars that sits in the upper left side representing the [[Virgin Mary]]; originally the star was a six-pointed star but quickly was corrected into the correct version. The second is the cross that appears on the right side of the crest. It is the [[Calvary]] Cross, which represents the place where Jesus was crucified while also representing Christianity. Third directly below the star, is an A imposed over an M, a common symbol for [[Ave Maria]], which is Latin for Hail Mary. The fourth is the [[Saint symbology|Eagle]] situated across the top section of the shield, which represents [[John the Apostle|St John]]. In the shield's compartment is the College's motto.\n\n=== House system ===\nThe current house system was bought into the College in 1999, and was named after early Catholic missionaries who came to New Zealand. All except Redwood are French, and staff and students pronounce them in the traditional ways. The names and colours of the St John's College Houses are:\n\n* '''Colin''' \u2013 green\n* '''Forest''' \u2013 yellow\n* '''Redwood''' \u2013 red\n* '''Reignier''' \u2013 blue\n\n==Curriculum==\n\n=== Academic results ===\nThe number of students achieving national qualifications is well above the national mean for similar decile schools at all levels of NCEA.  The percentage of students obtaining NCEA Level 1 increased from 61% in 2003 to 66% in 2004.  Levels of attainment in the literacy requirement have recently improved to the current level of over 91%.  Achievement in university entrance results has steadily improved over the past three years and is above the national average for schools at this decile level.\nThe percentage of Year 12 M\u0101ori students leaving school with qualifications is well above the national rates for schools in this decile.  Retention of M\u0101ori students to complete their Year 12 studies is high.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ero.govt.nz/ERO/reppub.nsf/Institution/0C81B79B808D45E2CC2571220004ABBD/$File/226.htm?OpenElement#_Toc128809659|title=Education Review Report|work=Education Review Office|date=February 2006|accessdate=18 July 2008}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n==Co-curriculum==\n\n=== Sport ===\nPlaying a winter sport is compulsory for junior students (Year 9 and 10) to encourage social integration into the college environment. Although sport is not compulsory in the senior years, the majority of seniors participate in sport with large numbers competing in the Summer sports offered. \n[[Rugby union|Rugby]] is the most popular sport at the college and enjoys a large following from St John's old boys. There are at least 8 teams, which does not include special teams selected for events like the Under 15s tournament and the Father Fisher trophy.\nSoccer is widely played at the college, and with [[hockey]] make up the rest of the majority of winter sport participants. There are also teams for [[basketball]], [[badminton]], [[squash (sport)|squash]], [[table tennis]], [[athletics (sport)|athletics]], swimming, [[tennis]], [[orienteering]], [[canoe polo]] and [[Touch football (rugby league)|touch]]. [[Cricket]] is by far the largest sport during the summer. The Cricket teams are usually divided into Hastings or Napier teams in lower grades.\n\nMany inter school sporting events take place, most notably with Catholic schools around the lower North Island. The main rivalry remains with other Marist Schools [[St. Patrick's College, Silverstream|St Pat's Silverstream]] and [[St. Patrick's College, Wellington|St Pat's Town]] in [[Wellington]], [[Hato Paora College|Hato Paora]] in the [[Manawatu-Wanganui|Manawatu]], and [[St. John's College, Hamilton|St Johns]] in [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]].\n\n===Religion===\nAs a Catholic school, religion plays an important factor in the day-to-day lives of St John's College students. As well as participating in Masses and Chapel, prayers are formally conducted at staff meetings, in form classes to start the day, at assemblies and at school meetings.\n\n===Kapa Haka===\nSt John's College has a long and proud tradition of [[Kapa haka]]. Along with [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] studies, students actively participate in M\u0101ori cultural activities like the inter house Haka competition.\n\n== Notable alumni ==\n* [[Greg Cooper (rugby union)|Greg Cooper]] \u2013 former All Black.\n* [[Matthew Cooper (rugby union)|Matt Cooper]] \u2013 former All Black.\n* [[Air New Zealand|Greg Foran]] \u2013 Air New Zealand CEO, former President and CEO [[Walmart]] USA.\n* [[Paul Martin (bishop)|Paul Martin]] (born 1967) \u2013 Roman Catholic Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Christchurch|Christchurch]].\n*[[Dean Parker]] - Arts Foundation Laureate\n*[[Brian Roche (business executive)|Brian Roche]] {{post-nominals|country=NZL|KNZM|size=85%}} \u2013 business executive.\n* [[John Scott (architect)|John Scott]] \u2013 architect.\n*[[Gerard van Bohemen|Gerard Van Bohemen]] \u2013 Justice of the High Court of New Zealand, former Permanent Representative of New Zealand to the United Nations.\n*[[Michael Wintringham]] \u2013 former State Services Commissioner.\n*[[Eric Young (broadcaster)|Eric Young]] \u2013 lead news anchor, [[Prime Television New Zealand|Prime News]], New Zealand.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.stjohns.school.nz/ Official site]\n\n{{Schools in Hawke's Bay}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint John's College, Hastings}}\n[[Category:Boys' schools in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1941]]\n[[Category:Schools in Hastings, New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Catholic secondary schools in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:1941 establishments in New Zealand]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|other schools of the same name|Saint John's College (disambiguation){{!}}Saint John's College}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2019}}\n \n{{Infobox school\n|name         = St John's College\n|image        = \n|motto        = {{ubl|{{lang-la|[[List of Latin phrases (M-O)|Opere et Veritate]]}}|(\"In Word and in Deed\")}}\n|established  = 1941; {{years ago|1941}} years ago\n|type         = [[Secondary education in New Zealand|State Integrated]], [[Single-sex school|Single-sex]], [[Day school|Day]], Secondary (Year 9\u201313)\n|denomination = [[Catholic Church in New Zealand|Catholic]] \n|principal    = Paul Melloy\n|fees         = \n|city         = [[Hastings, New Zealand|Hastings]]\n|state        = [[Hawkes Bay]]\n|country      = [[New Zealand]] {{flagicon|New Zealand}}\n|coordinates  = {{coord|39|38|22|S|176|51|22|E|display=inline,title}}\n|roll = {{NZ school roll data|226|y||y}} <small>({{NZ school roll data|||y}})</small>\n|num_employ   = ~ 35 (full time)\n|decile =  4K<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.minedu.govt.nz/~/media/MinEdu/Files/EducationSectors/PrimarySecondary/SchoolOpsResourcing/OperationalFundingDeciles/DecileChanges_20142015.xls |title= Decile Change 2014 to 2015 for State & State Integrated Schools |publisher= Ministry of Education |accessdate= 12 February 2015}}</ref>\n|MOE =  226\n|revenue      = \n|colours      = Maroon, blue and white\n|homepage     = [http://www.stjohns.school.nz/ www.stjohns.school.nz]\n}}\n\n'''St John's College''' is a [[Secondary education in New Zealand|State Integrated]], [[Catholic Church in New Zealand|Catholic]], [[Day School]] for boys, located in [[Hastings, New Zealand|Hastings]], a provincial city in [[Hawkes Bay]], New Zealand.\n\nFounded in 1941 by the [[Society of Mary (Marists)|Marist Fathers]], St John's College has a non-selective enrolment policy (although gives preference to students from Catholic families) and currently caters for approximately 450 students from Year 9 (3rd Form) to Year 13 (7th Form).\n\nSt John's College has a diverse, multicultural roll. In 2006 its ethnic composition was P\u0101keh\u0101 73%, M\u0101ori 23%, and Pacific 4%\n.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ero.govt.nz/ERO/reppub.nsf/Institution/0C81B79B808D45E2CC2571220004ABBD/$File/226.htm?OpenElement#_Toc128809659|title=Education Review Report|work=Education Review Office|date=February 2006|accessdate=18 July 2008}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> The college excels in sporting and cultural activities. Academically, the school offers for senior years the [[National Certificate of Educational Achievement]] assessment system (NCEA).\n\nSt John's College is the oldest private/state integrated secondary for boys in New Zealand outside the traditional main centres of Auckland, Wellington, Christchurch, and Dunedin ([[Te Aute College]], also in Hawke's Bay was previously the title holder but became coed during the 1990s).\n\n== History ==\nSt John's College was established in 1941, on Frederick St, Hastings (the current site of St Mary's Primary School).  It was founded by the [[Society of Mary (Marists)|Marist Fathers]] in response to the lack of Catholic education for young men in Hawkes Bay. It was also to be a brother school to the already established all girls [[Sacred Heart College, Napier]], some 20&nbsp;km north.\n\nEnrolment proved so popular that the school needed to expand, so in 1956, with an allotment of donated land, St John's College moved to its present site on Jervois St, Mayfair. Old boys recall that on the day of the move, they carried the school furniture, back and forth to the new premises over 3&nbsp;km away, and still had to attend afternoon class. The roll grew more slowly after that. Part of the problem was the transportation of students from around the Hawkes Bay region as many students from Napier found it difficult to reach school before school bus lines were established. There were even calls to make both Sacred Heart and St Johns co-ed, to prevent Napier boys travelling to Hastings and Hastings girls travelling to Napier. Today this issue is non-existent, although around 40% of St John's College students come from the Napier area.\n\nIn 1975, St John's College was \"integrated\" into the state system under the ''Private Schools Conditional Integration Act 1975''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.govt.nz/libraries/contents/om_isapi.dll?clientID=3690096234&hitsperheading=on&infobase=pal_statutes.nfo&record=%7b3AAAD062%7d&softpage=DOC|title=Education Review Report|work=Education Review Office|date=February 2006|access-date=18 July 2008|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716023004/http://www.legislation.govt.nz/libraries/contents/om_isapi.dll?clientID=3690096234&hitsperheading=on&infobase=pal_statutes.nfo&record=%7b3AAAD062%7d&softpage=DOC|archive-date=16 July 2011|df=}}</ref> \"on a basis which will preserve and safeguard the special character of the education provided by them\".\n\nOver time St John's quietly expanded with the addition of new buildings and land. The 1990s saw drastic changes with the completion of 'The Centre' (the school gymnasium), the music suite and geography room, and the purchase of the old Firth industrial land to expand the playing fields. This gave St John's an additional rugby field, a new area for cricket nets, and another drive way towards Karamu road with additional car spaces. Since 2000 several remodels have been undertaken and includes the construction of the new technology wing.\n\nSt John's College celebrated its 50th Jubilee in 1991 which was easily the colleges biggest event ever. An abundance of old boys returned for the weekend and included several speakers and functions as well as a variety of activities and inter house competitions for the students.\n\nIn May 2014, the school suspended student Lucan Battison over the length of his hair.<ref>[http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/tweets-over-suspended-student-lands-schoolgirl-in-hotwater-6005703 Tweets over suspended student lands schoolgirl in hotwater]</ref> The family took the school to the High Court,<ref>[http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/back-school-boy-while-judge-ponders-long-hair-6009989 Back to school for boy while judge ponders long hair]</ref> where they won against the school.<ref>[http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/education/10207087/Lucan-Battison-wins-long-hair-court-battle Lucan Battison wins long-hair court battle]</ref>\n\n== Campus ==\nSt John's College is situated on Jervois St, Mayfair, in Hastings' northern suburbs. The site layout has all academic buildings close to the main road and are named after former rectors of the school, for example 'The Dowling Block' which contains the Library and Humanities subjects. Behind the buildings are the school playing fields, which separate the swimming pool and the tennis courts from the academic areas.\n\n===Facilities===\nCurrent facilities of St John's include:\n*'The Centre', which is a gymnasium used for sports, games and [[physical education]] (PE) classes. Also used as the venue for weekly Wednesday assemblies and other official school occasions such as college masses and the Year 12 Leavers' Mass.\n*The Kenneth Guthrie Pool, located at the rear of the school property, next to the tennis courts.\n*Playing Fields, which consists of a variety of interconnected fields containing two rugby fields, a cricket pitch and soccer field, field hockey students practice at Park Island Sports Ground in Napier.\n\n==St John's tradition==\n\n=== Crest ===\n\nThe school [[Coat of arms|crest]] incorporates four symbols. It incorporates the major elements of Archbishop Redwood's Crest the star and the AM as well as the \"Redwood Cross\" i.e. the cross on top of a pile of rocks. The five 5 pointed stars that sits in the upper left side representing the [[Virgin Mary]]; originally the star was a six-pointed star but quickly was corrected into the correct version. The second is the cross that appears on the right side of the crest. It is the [[Calvary]] Cross, which represents the place where Jesus was crucified while also representing Christianity. Third directly below the star, is an A imposed over an M, a common symbol for [[Ave Maria]], which is Latin for Hail Mary. The fourth is the [[Saint symbology|Eagle]] situated across the top section of the shield, which represents [[John the Apostle|St John]]. In the shield's compartment is the College's motto.\n\n=== House system ===\nThe current house system was bought into the College in 1999, and was named after early Catholic missionaries who came to New Zealand. All except Redwood are French, and staff and students pronounce them in the traditional ways. The names and colours of the St John's College Houses are:\n\n* '''Colin''' \u2013 green\n* '''Forest''' \u2013 yellow\n* '''Redwood''' \u2013 red\n* '''Reignier''' \u2013 blue\n\n==Curriculum==\n\n=== Academic results ===\nThe number of students achieving national qualifications is well above the national mean for similar decile schools at all levels of NCEA.  The percentage of students obtaining NCEA Level 1 increased from 61% in 2003 to 66% in 2004.  Levels of attainment in the literacy requirement have recently improved to the current level of over 91%.  Achievement in university entrance results has steadily improved over the past three years and is above the national average for schools at this decile level.\nThe percentage of Year 12 M\u0101ori students leaving school with qualifications is well above the national rates for schools in this decile.  Retention of M\u0101ori students to complete their Year 12 studies is high.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ero.govt.nz/ERO/reppub.nsf/Institution/0C81B79B808D45E2CC2571220004ABBD/$File/226.htm?OpenElement#_Toc128809659|title=Education Review Report|work=Education Review Office|date=February 2006|accessdate=18 July 2008}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n==Co-curriculum==\n\n=== Sport ===\nPlaying a winter sport is compulsory for junior students (Year 9 and 10) to encourage social integration into the college environment. Although sport is not compulsory in the senior years, the majority of seniors participate in sport with large numbers competing in the Summer sports offered. \n[[Rugby union|Rugby]] is the most popular sport at the college and enjoys a large following from St John's old boys. There are at least 8 teams, which does not include special teams selected for events like the Under 15s tournament and the Father Fisher trophy.\nSoccer is widely played at the college, and with [[hockey]] make up the rest of the majority of winter sport participants. There are also teams for [[basketball]], [[badminton]], [[squash (sport)|squash]], [[table tennis]], [[athletics (sport)|athletics]], swimming, [[tennis]], [[orienteering]], [[canoe polo]] and [[Touch football (rugby league)|touch]]. [[Cricket]] is by far the largest sport during the summer. The Cricket teams are usually divided into Hastings or Napier teams in lower grades.\n\nMany inter school sporting events take place, most notably with Catholic schools around the lower North Island. The main rivalry remains with other Marist Schools [[St. Patrick's College, Silverstream|St Pat's Silverstream]] and [[St. Patrick's College, Wellington|St Pat's Town]] in [[Wellington]], [[Hato Paora College|Hato Paora]] in the [[Manawatu-Wanganui|Manawatu]], and [[St. John's College, Hamilton|St Johns]] in [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]].\n\n===Religion===\nAs a Catholic school, religion plays an important factor in the day-to-day lives of St John's College students. As well as participating in Masses and Chapel, prayers are formally conducted at staff meetings, in form classes to start the day, at assemblies and at school meetings.\n\n===Kapa Haka===\nSt John's College has a long and proud tradition of [[Kapa haka]]. Along with [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] studies, students actively participate in M\u0101ori cultural activities like the inter house Haka competition.\n\n== Notable alumni ==\n* [[Greg Cooper (rugby union)|Greg Cooper]] \u2013 former All Black.\n* [[Matthew Cooper (rugby union)|Matt Cooper]] \u2013 former All Black.\n* [[Air New Zealand|Greg Foran]] \u2013 Air New Zealand CEO, former President and CEO [[Walmart]] USA.\n* [[Paul Martin (bishop)|Paul Martin]] (born 1967) \u2013 Roman Catholic Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Christchurch|Christchurch]].\n*[[Dean Parker]] - Arts Foundation Laureate\n*[[Brian Roche (business executive)|Sir Brian Roche]] \u2013 business executive.\n* [[John Scott (architect)|John Scott]] \u2013 architect.\n*[[Gerard van Bohemen|Gerard Van Bohemen]] \u2013 Justice of the High Court of New Zealand, former Permanent Representative of New Zealand to the United Nations.\n*[[Michael Wintringham]] \u2013 former State Services Commissioner.\n*[[Eric Young (broadcaster)|Eric Young]] \u2013 lead news anchor, [[Prime Television New Zealand|Prime News]], New Zealand.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.stjohns.school.nz/ Official site]\n\n{{Schools in Hawke's Bay}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint John's College, Hastings}}\n[[Category:Boys' schools in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1941]]\n[[Category:Schools in Hastings, New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Catholic secondary schools in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:1941 establishments in New Zealand]]\n", "name_user": "Emendment", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable alumni:no honorific", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St_John%27s_College,_Hastings"}
{"title_page": "Arev Petrosyan", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| bgcolour      = \n| image         = \u0531\u0580\u0587 \u054a\u0565\u057f\u0580\u0578\u057d\u0575\u0561\u0576, \u0581\u0578\u0582\u0581\u0561\u0570\u0561\u0576\u0564\u0565\u057d, 2008.jpg\n| imagesize     = \n| name          = Arev Petrosyan<br>\u0531\u0580\u0587 \u054a\u0565\u057f\u0580\u0578\u057d\u0575\u0561\u0576 \n| birth_name    = Arevik Petrosyan\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1972|5|6}}\n| birth_place   = [[Yerevan]], Armenia\n| field          = Painter, professor\n| nationality   = [[Armenians|Armenian]]\n}}\n\n'''Arev Petrosyan''' ({{Lang-hy|\u0531\u0580\u0587 \u054a\u0565\u057f\u0580\u0578\u057d\u0575\u0561\u0576}}; born May 6, 1972 in [[Yerevan]]), is an [[Armenians|Armenian]] artist. Honored artist of the Republic of Armenia (2015).<ref>[http://www.president.am/hy/decrees/item/2168/ \u0531. \u0532. \u054a\u0535\u054f\u0550\u0548\u054d\u0545\u0531\u0546\u053b\u0546 \u0540\u0531\u0545\u0531\u054d\u054f\u0531\u0546\u053b \u0540\u0531\u0546\u0550\u0531\u054a\u0535\u054f\u0548\u0552\u0539\u0545\u0531\u0546 \u054e\u0531\u054d\u054f\u0531\u053f\u0531\u054e\u0548\u0550 \u0546\u053f\u0531\u0550\u0549\u053b \u054a\u0531\u054f\u054e\u0531\u054e\u0548\u0550 \u053f\u0548\u0549\u0548\u0552\u0544 \u0547\u0546\u0548\u0550\u0540\u0535\u053c\u0548\u0552 \u0544\u0531\u054d\u053b\u0546]</ref><ref>[http://www.yerkir.am/news/view/93110.html Serzh Sargsyan awarded Hrant Tokhatian, Valery Osipov, Artur Aleksanyan (photos)]</ref><ref>[http://www.panorama.am/am/news/2015/09/21/amiryan-poghosyan-petrosyan/1448742 Arev Petrosyan was awarded the honorary title of the Honored Artist of the Republic of Armenia]</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:\u0531\u0580\u0587 \u054a\u0565\u057f\u0580\u0578\u057d\u0575\u0561\u0576, 2009.jpg|thumb]]\nArev (Arevik) Petrosyan was born on May 6, 1972 in Yerevan, Armenia, in the family of the sculptor Benik Petrosyan and violinist, pedagogue, public figure Alice Adamyan.\n\n1987-1991 Arev studied at Panos Terlemezyan College of Fine Arts in the faculty of design, 1991-1995 she studied Computer Graphics and \u201cManagement and administration\u201d and in 1991-1998 she was enrolled in the Yerevan State Academy of Arts (faculty of ceramics, art). In 1999 Arev became a member of the Artists' Union of Armenia. In 2014 she donated her artwork \u201cLOVE\u201d to the [[Aiwa|AIWA]] organization in [[San Francisco]]. In 2013 Arev was included in \u201cWomen in Art\u201d volume 1 series of book From Middle Ages to the Modern Art Era. In 2014 Arev Petrosyan's 8,40 x 2,40 meters art work was presented and donated to Holy Trinity Church in [[Fresno, California|Fresno]] for 100 Year Anniversary of the first Armenian church in United States. In 2015 Arev opened AREV ART GALLERY in the center of Yerevan. In 2015 she was awarded as an honored artist of Republic of Armenia.<ref>[http://www.orran.am/docs/Orran_Newsletter_Dec_2009.pdf/  Fundraising, Orran]</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LXgiRJP-fJI/ Fund of Armenia Children (COAF) fundraising gala evening]</ref> \n\nDuring the period of 1995-2007 Arev has designed number of television studios upon order of the Armenian National \ntelevision Company as well as other agencies and television companies\u2013the second channel, \u201cKaym\u201d, \u201cParadise\u201d, \u201cYerkir Media\u201d, \u201cSharm\u201d, \u201cShant\u201d, \u201cShoghakat\u201d, \u201cInternews\u201d, \u201cA1+\u2019\u2019, \u201cAR\u2019\u2019. She designed the information pavilions of the [[Government of Armenia]], Ministry of Jurisdiction, \u201cCity FM\u201d radio station. Worked with famous companies as iCon Communication, Schwarzkoph, Coca-Cola. Aesthetic design of television movies \u201cNew Year\u201d. She has been the art director in the film \u201cPath\u201d (directed by Ruben Qochar, USA-Armenia). She has done stage design for concerts, staging, different occasions, interior and exterior design of cottages, offices, restaurants, apartments and places.\n\n* Honored Artist of the RA\n* Member of the Artists\u2019 Union of the RA\n* CEO of \u201cBenik Petrosyan\u201d cultural fund (1997)\n* Founder of Arev Art Gallery (2015)\n\nFounder of \u201cNOOSH AREVI\u201d  Armenian brand of clothing, bags, scarfs and assessors, home deco and  furniture production based on national heritage, which will be launched in spring 2018.\n\n2007-2017 donated artworks for charity \u201cORRAN\u201d organization, she is one of GOLD donators.\n\n==AREV ART GALLERY==\nIn 2015 opened AREV ART GALLERY in the center of Yerevan. Along with Arev's work, on display are her brother - Areg Petrosyan's sculptures, as well as her late father Benik Petrosyan's masterpieces. \n\nThis art center became a favorite place for residents of Yerevan and its guests. Being famous public person, she is connecting people and bringing to life cultural events and social projects\n\n==Exhibitions==\n* Exhibition at American University of Armenia /AUA/ within \u201cEmpowerment of Girls and Women  in   Armenia\u201d conference, 2017 \n* Exhibition at German Embassy in Armenia dedicated to women, 2017 \n* \u201cArmenian culture week\u201d in [[Tokyo]], 2016 \n* \u201cWomen\u2019s role in sustainable development\u201d in [[Paris]] in [[UNESCO]] house, 2016\n* Arev Petrosyan for [[American University of Armenia]] (AUA), 2015<ref>[http://newsroom.aua.am/2015/09/26/akian-art-gallery-exhibits-work-by-renowned-armenian-artist-arev-petrosyan/ Akian Art Gallery Exhibits Work by Renowned Armenian Artist Arev Petrosyan]</ref>\n* Beirut Art Fair 2014. GALA ART GALLERY's booth, 2014\n* Monaco Art Fair 2014 SHEDEVR Art GALLERY's booth, 2014\n* Holy Trinity Armenian Church in Fresno, Exhibition and donation of two paintings to the church, 2013\n* [[Council of Europe]], [[Strasbourg]] - stained glass picture \u201cPower of Unity\u201d which was put on display at the Assembly Hall, 2013\n* Exhibition of triptych \u201cPower of Unity\u201d at the hall of the [[Ministerial Committee]], 2013\n* Exhibition in Belarus, Armenian days in [[Minsk]], 2013\n* Exhibition of triptych in [[National Gallery of Armenia]] \u201cBOOK 500\u201d, 2012\n* \u201cWoman in Art\u201d exhibition in Artists' Union of Armenia, 2012\n* Woman Business Forum, 2012\n* Exhibition in Beirut, 2012\n* Exhibition in Armenian Consulate, Los Angeles, USA, 2012\n* Project \u201cGenocide 100\u201d. Pray (AXOTQ), 2011\n* Opening of \u201cArev Art Show Room\u201d in [[Moscow]], 2011\n* \u201cColors from Armenia\u201d, Beirut, 2011<ref>[http://www.artgallery.hamazkayin.com/news/colors-from-armenia-arev-petrosyans-exhibition  \"Colors from Armenia\": Arev PETROSYAN Exhibition]</ref>\n* Exhibition at the National Assembly of the Republic of Armenia, Yerevan, 2010\n* Armenian days in Georgia, Tbilisi, 2010\n* American University of Armenia (AUA), 2010\n* Exhibition in American Embassy, Yerevan, 2010\n* Exhibition & Presentation of Catalogue and DVD \u201cReflection and Looking, 2009\n* \u201cMy golden city\u201d dedicated to the 2790th anniversary of Yerevan, Artists' Union of Armenia, 2008\n* \u201cDedication\u201d to the memory of Arev Petrosyan's father sculptor Benik Petrosyan, National Gallery of Armenia (family exhibition)Yerevan, 2008 \n* The Third [[Beijing]] International Art Biennale, China, 2008\n* 75th Anniversary of the Union of Painters of Armenia, Artists' Union of Armenia, Yerevan, 2008\n* III forum of artistic and scientific clerisy of [[CIS countries]], [[Tajikistan]], [[Dushanbe]], 2008\n* \u201c[[March 8th]] - International Women\u2019s day\u201d by the patronage of the First Lady of the Republic of Armenia, Yerevan, 2007\n* Exhibitions National Assembly of the Republic of Armenia, Yerevan, 2006\n* \u201cWoman Painters of Armenia\u201d, Hamazgayin, Yerevan, 2006\n* \u201cWomen\u2019s Art\u201d The Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Armenia, 2005\n* AOKS, Yerevan, Armenia, 2005\n* \u201cMy Flowers to the Martyrs\u201d dedicated to the 90th anniversary of the Armenian, 2005\n* \u201cWomen for peace\u201d [[UNIFEM]], Yerevan (was awarded a prize), 2002\n* United Nations office, Yerevan, 2001\n* UNESCO student camps, Yerevan, 1999\n* Number of exhibitions in the Republic of Armenian, also foreign exhibitions, 1991-1995\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"140\" heights=\"140\"> \n\"CONTINUUM\" 2012.jpg\n\"EXPECTATION\" 2011.jpg\n\"MOTHER ARMENIA\" 2008.jpg\n\"BACK LOOK\" 2012 Series of Paintings,threesome.jpg\n\"TREE OF LIFE\" 2013.jpg\n\"MIDNIGHT\" 2013.jpg\n\"MY BELIEF\" 2013.jpg\n\"MY WORLD\" 2013.jpg\n\"NOW, BEFORE, AFTER\" 2013.jpg\n\"LOVE\" 2013 POWER OF UNITY.jpg\n\"FREEDOM\" 2013 POWER OF UNITY.jpg\n\"MIND\" 2013 POWER OF UNITY.jpg\n\"UNIVERSE\" 2012.jpg\n\"SUMMER\" 2011.JPG \n\"THREE GRACES\" 2008.jpg\n\"GOOD MORNING\" 2013.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Armenian artists]]\n*[[List of Armenians]]\n*[[Culture of Armenia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.arev-art.com/ Official web page]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERWuQT8EWBw Gorgeous woman creates magnificent works of art]\n* [http://www.shoghakat.am/am/telecasts/352/ Arev Petrosyan]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qK2bU4CarjM My Library, Arev Petrosyan]\n* [http://gala-artgallery.am/artist/arev-petrosyan/ Gala Art Gallery, Arev Petrosyan]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2wZ5Kv2l33k \u0544\u0565\u0580\u0578\u0576\u0584 \u0531\u0580\u0587 \u054a\u0565\u057f\u0580\u0578\u057d\u0575\u0561\u0576]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j2cUWLp2pjw Arev Petrosyan]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fWQS154PalY \u0532\u0561\u0580\u0587, \u0565\u057d \u0565\u0574 \u0531\u0580\u0587 \u054a\u0565\u057f\u0580\u0578\u057d\u0575\u0561\u0576 19 06 17]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AvYpYnKN1Yw Arev Art Gallery - \u0531\u0580\u0587 \u054a\u0565\u057f\u0580\u0578\u057d\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u0551\u0578\u0582\u0581\u0561\u057d\u0580\u0561\u0570]\n* [http://worldartdalia.blogspot.am/2015/05/blog-post_85.html \u0425\u0443\u0434\u043e\u0436\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0438 \u043f\u043e \u0441\u0442\u0435\u043a\u043b\u0443. \u0410\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0438\u043a \u0411\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0441\u044f\u043d]\n* [http://mirtv.ru/video/16783/ \u0410\u0440\u0435\u0432 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0441\u044f\u043d \u0440\u0438\u0441\u0443\u0435\u0442 \u0437\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0442\u043e\u043c \u0438 \u0441\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0440\u043e\u043c]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petrosyan, Arev}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Armenian painters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Yerevan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| bgcolour      = \n| image         = \u0531\u0580\u0587 \u054a\u0565\u057f\u0580\u0578\u057d\u0575\u0561\u0576, \u0581\u0578\u0582\u0581\u0561\u0570\u0561\u0576\u0564\u0565\u057d, 2008.jpg\n| imagesize     = \n| name          = Arev Petrosyan<br>\u0531\u0580\u0587 \u054a\u0565\u057f\u0580\u0578\u057d\u0575\u0561\u0576 \n| birth_name    = Arevik Petrosyan\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1972|5|6}}\n| birth_place   = [[Yerevan]], Armenia\n| field          = Painter, professor\n| nationality   = [[Armenians|Armenian]]\n}}\n\n'''Arev Petrosyan''' ({{Lang-hy|\u0531\u0580\u0587 \u054a\u0565\u057f\u0580\u0578\u057d\u0575\u0561\u0576}}; born May 6, 1972 in [[Yerevan]]), is an [[Armenians|Armenian]] artist. Honored artist of the Republic of Armenia (2015).<ref>[http://www.president.am/hy/decrees/item/2168/ \u0531. \u0532. \u054a\u0535\u054f\u0550\u0548\u054d\u0545\u0531\u0546\u053b\u0546 \u0540\u0531\u0545\u0531\u054d\u054f\u0531\u0546\u053b \u0540\u0531\u0546\u0550\u0531\u054a\u0535\u054f\u0548\u0552\u0539\u0545\u0531\u0546 \u054e\u0531\u054d\u054f\u0531\u053f\u0531\u054e\u0548\u0550 \u0546\u053f\u0531\u0550\u0549\u053b \u054a\u0531\u054f\u054e\u0531\u054e\u0548\u0550 \u053f\u0548\u0549\u0548\u0552\u0544 \u0547\u0546\u0548\u0550\u0540\u0535\u053c\u0548\u0552 \u0544\u0531\u054d\u053b\u0546]</ref><ref>[http://www.yerkir.am/news/view/93110.html Serzh Sargsyan awarded Hrant Tokhatian, Valery Osipov, Artur Aleksanyan (photos)]</ref><ref>[http://www.panorama.am/am/news/2015/09/21/amiryan-poghosyan-petrosyan/1448742 Arev Petrosyan was awarded the honorary title of the Honored Artist of the Republic of Armenia]</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:\u0531\u0580\u0587 \u054a\u0565\u057f\u0580\u0578\u057d\u0575\u0561\u0576, 2009.jpg|thumb]]\nArev (Arevik) Petrosyan was born on May 6, 1972 in Yerevan, Armenia, in the family of the sculptor Benik Petrosyan and violinist, pedagogue, public figure Alice Adamyan.\n\n1987-1991 Arev studied at Panos Terlemezyan College of Fine Arts in the faculty of design, 1991-1995 she studied Computer Graphics and \u201cManagement and administration\u201d and in 1991-1998 she was enrolled in the Yerevan State Academy of Arts (faculty of ceramics, art). In 1999 Arev became a member of the Artists' Union of Armenia. In 2014 she donated her artwork \u201cLOVE\u201d to the [[Aiwa|AIWA]] organization in [[San Francisco]]. In 2013 Arev was included in \u201cWomen in Art\u201d volume 1 series of book From Middle Ages to the Modern Art Era. In 2014 Arev Petrosyan's 8,40 x 2,40 meters art work was presented and donated to Holy Trinity Church in [[Fresno, California|Fresno]] for 100 Year Anniversary of the first Armenian church in United States. In 2015 Arev opened AREV ART GALLERY in the center of Yerevan. In 2015 she was awarded as an honored artist of Republic of Armenia.<ref>[http://www.orran.am/docs/Orran_Newsletter_Dec_2009.pdf/  Fundraising, Orran]</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LXgiRJP-fJI/ Fund of Armenia Children (COAF) fundraising gala evening]</ref> \n\nDuring the period of 1995-2007 Arev has designed number of television studios upon order of the Armenian National \ntelevision Company as well as other agencies and television companies\u2013the second channel, \u201cKaym\u201d, \u201cParadise\u201d, \u201cYerkir Media\u201d, \u201cSharm\u201d, \u201cShant\u201d, \u201cShoghakat\u201d, \u201cInternews\u201d, \u201cA1+\u2019\u2019, \u201cAR\u2019\u2019. She designed the information pavilions of the [[Government of Armenia]], Ministry of Jurisdiction, \u201cCity FM\u201d radio station. Worked with famous companies as iCon Communication, Schwarzkoph, Coca-Cola. Aesthetic design of television movies \u201cNew Year\u201d. She has been the art director in the film \u201cPath\u201d (directed by Ruben Qochar, USA-Armenia). She has done stage design for concerts, staging, different occasions, interior and exterior design of cottages, offices, restaurants, apartments and places.\n\n* Honored Artist of the RA\n* Member of the Artists\u2019 Union of the RA\n* CEO of \u201cBenik Petrosyan\u201d cultural fund (1997)\n* Founder of Arev Art Gallery (2015)\n\nFounder of \u201cNOOSH AREVI\u201d  Armenian brand of clothing, bags, scarfs and assessors, home deco and  furniture production based on national heritage, which will be launched in spring 2018.\n\n2007-2017 donated artworks for charity \u201cORRAN\u201d organization, she is one of GOLD donators.\n\n==AREV ART GALLERY==\nIn 2015 opened AREV ART GALLERY in the center of Yerevan. Along with Arev's work, on display are her brother - Areg Petrosyan's sculptures, as well as her late father Benik Petrosyan's masterpieces. \n\nThis art center became a favorite place for residents of Yerevan and its guests. Being famous public person, she is connecting people and bringing to life cultural events and social projects\n\n==Exhibitions==\n* Exhibition at American University of Armenia /AUA/ within \u201cEmpowerment of Girls and Women  in   Armenia\u201d conference, 2017 \n* Exhibition at German Embassy in Armenia dedicated to women, 2017 \n* \u201cArmenian culture week\u201d in [[Tokyo]], 2016 \n* \u201cWomen\u2019s role in sustainable development\u201d in [[Paris]] in [[UNESCO]] house, 2016\n* Arev Petrosyan for [[American University of Armenia]] (AUA), 2015<ref>[http://newsroom.aua.am/2015/09/26/akian-art-gallery-exhibits-work-by-renowned-armenian-artist-arev-petrosyan/ Akian Art Gallery Exhibits Work by Renowned Armenian Artist Arev Petrosyan]</ref>\n* Beirut Art Fair 2014. GALA ART GALLERY's booth, 2014\n* Monaco Art Fair 2014 SHEDEVR Art GALLERY's booth, 2014\n* Holy Trinity Armenian Church in Fresno, Exhibition and donation of two paintings to the church, 2013\n* [[Council of Europe]], [[Strasbourg]] - stained glass picture \u201cPower of Unity\u201d which was put on display at the Assembly Hall, 2013\n* Exhibition of triptych \u201cPower of Unity\u201d at the hall of the [[Ministerial Committee]] , 2013\n* Exhibition in Belarus, Armenian days in [[Minsk]], 2013\n* Exhibition of triptych in [[National Gallery of Armenia]] \u201cBOOK 500\u201d, 2012\n* \u201cWoman in Art\u201d exhibition in Artists' Union of Armenia, 2012\n* Woman Business Forum, 2012\n* Exhibition in Beirut, 2012\n* Exhibition in Armenian Consulate, Los Angeles, USA, 2012\n* Project \u201cGenocide 100\u201d. Pray (AXOTQ), 2011\n* Opening of \u201cArev Art Show Room\u201d in [[Moscow]], 2011\n* \u201cColors from Armenia\u201d, Beirut, 2011<ref>[http://www.artgallery.hamazkayin.com/news/colors-from-armenia-arev-petrosyans-exhibition  \"Colors from Armenia\": Arev PETROSYAN Exhibition]</ref>\n* Exhibition at the National Assembly of the Republic of Armenia, Yerevan, 2010\n* Armenian days in Georgia, Tbilisi, 2010\n* American University of Armenia (AUA), 2010\n* Exhibition in American Embassy, Yerevan, 2010\n* Exhibition & Presentation of Catalogue and DVD \u201cReflection and Looking, 2009\n* \u201cMy golden city\u201d dedicated to the 2790th anniversary of Yerevan, Artists' Union of Armenia, 2008\n* \u201cDedication\u201d to the memory of Arev Petrosyan's father sculptor Benik Petrosyan, National Gallery of Armenia (family exhibition)Yerevan, 2008 \n* The Third [[Beijing]] International Art Biennale, China, 2008\n* 75th Anniversary of the Union of Painters of Armenia, Artists' Union of Armenia, Yerevan, 2008\n* III forum of artistic and scientific clerisy of [[CIS countries]], [[Tajikistan]], [[Dushanbe]], 2008\n* \u201c[[March 8th]] - International Women\u2019s day\u201d by the patronage of the First Lady of the Republic of Armenia, Yerevan, 2007\n* Exhibitions National Assembly of the Republic of Armenia, Yerevan, 2006\n* \u201cWoman Painters of Armenia\u201d, Hamazgayin, Yerevan, 2006\n* \u201cWomen\u2019s Art\u201d The Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Armenia, 2005\n* AOKS, Yerevan, Armenia, 2005\n* \u201cMy Flowers to the Martyrs\u201d dedicated to the 90th anniversary of the Armenian, 2005\n* \u201cWomen for peace\u201d [[UNIFEM]], Yerevan (was awarded a prize), 2002\n* United Nations office, Yerevan, 2001\n* UNESCO student camps, Yerevan, 1999\n* Number of exhibitions in the Republic of Armenian, also foreign exhibitions, 1991-1995\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"140\" heights=\"140\"> \n\"CONTINUUM\" 2012.jpg\n\"EXPECTATION\" 2011.jpg\n\"MOTHER ARMENIA\" 2008.jpg\n\"BACK LOOK\" 2012 Series of Paintings,threesome.jpg\n\"TREE OF LIFE\" 2013.jpg\n\"MIDNIGHT\" 2013.jpg\n\"MY BELIEF\" 2013.jpg\n\"MY WORLD\" 2013.jpg\n\"NOW, BEFORE, AFTER\" 2013.jpg\n\"LOVE\" 2013 POWER OF UNITY.jpg\n\"FREEDOM\" 2013 POWER OF UNITY.jpg\n\"MIND\" 2013 POWER OF UNITY.jpg\n\"UNIVERSE\" 2012.jpg\n\"SUMMER\" 2011.JPG \n\"THREE GRACES\" 2008.jpg\n\"GOOD MORNING\" 2013.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Armenian artists]]\n*[[List of Armenians]]\n*[[Culture of Armenia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.arev-art.com/ Official web page]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ERWuQT8EWBw Gorgeous woman creates magnificent works of art]\n* [http://www.shoghakat.am/am/telecasts/352/ Arev Petrosyan]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qK2bU4CarjM My Library, Arev Petrosyan]\n* [http://gala-artgallery.am/artist/arev-petrosyan/ Gala Art Gallery, 